
===================================
📌 1. Finglish Version (Persian Latin Script)
===================================

📖 **Tashrih:**
    Dastoor `mscompress` baraye feshorde kardan (compress) file-ha be formati ke Microsoft estefade mikonad (MS-DOS, Windows) be kar miravad. In kar be manzoore kam kardan hajm file va zakhire-sazi fazaye bishtar anjam mishavad.

⚙️ **Gozine-ha:**
    🔹 `mscompress file.txt compressed.txt`  --> 📝 File `file.txt` ra feshorde mikonad va ba name `compressed.txt` zakhire mikonad.
    🔹 `mscompress -d compressed.txt original.txt` --> 🔓 File feshorde shode `compressed.txt` ra baz mikonad (decompress) va ba name `original.txt` zakhire mikonad.

🛠 **Mesal-ha:**

    $ mscompress myfile.txt myfile.cmp

    🔹 File `myfile.txt` feshorde shode va ba name `myfile.cmp` zakhire mishavad.

    $ mscompress -d myfile.cmp myfile_original.txt

    🔹 File `myfile.cmp` baz shode va ba name `myfile_original.txt` zakhire mishavad.

✅ **Mesal sade:**

    $ mscompress document.txt document.cmp

    🔹 Dastoor file `document.txt` ra feshorde mikonad. Dar natije, hajm file kamtar mishavad, va `document.cmp` file jadidi ast ke file feshorde shode ra dar khod negah midarad.

===================================
📌 2. English Version
===================================

📖 **Description:**
    The `mscompress` command is used to compress files into a format used by Microsoft operating systems (MS-DOS, Windows). This is done to reduce file size and save storage space.

⚙️ **Options:**
    🔹 `mscompress file.txt compressed.txt`  --> 📝 Compresses the file `file.txt` and saves it as `compressed.txt`.
    🔹 `mscompress -d compressed.txt original.txt` --> 🔓 Decompresses the compressed file `compressed.txt` and saves it as `original.txt`.

🛠 **Examples:**

    $ mscompress myfile.txt myfile.cmp

    🔹 Compresses the file `myfile.txt` and saves it as `myfile.cmp`.

    $ mscompress -d myfile.cmp myfile_original.txt

    🔹 Decompresses the file `myfile.cmp` and saves it as `myfile_original.txt`.

✅ **Simple Example:**

    $ mscompress document.txt document.cmp

    🔹 The command compresses `document.txt`. As a result, the file size is reduced, and `document.cmp` is a new file containing the compressed data.
